SIMPLE: impious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impious
<hw>Im"pi*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>impius</ets>; pref. <ets>im-</ets> not + <ets>pius</ets> piou. See
<er>Pious</er>.]</ety> <def>Not pious; wanting piety; irreligious;
irreverent; ungodly; profane; wanting in reverence for the Supreme
Being; <as>as, an <ex>impious</ex> deed; <ex>impious</ex>
language.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When vice prevails, and <qex>impious</qex> men bear away,⟦br⟧
The post of honor is a private station.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Impious</er>, <er>Irreligious</er>,
<er>Profane</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Irreligious</xex> is negative,
<xex>impious</xex> and <xex>profane</xex> are positive. An indifferent
man may be <xex>irreligious</xex>; a <xex>profane</xex> man is
irreverent in speech and conduct; an <xex>impious</xex> man is wickedly
and boldly defiant in the strongest sense. <xex>Profane</xex> also has
the milder sense of <xex>secular</xex>.</usage> <rj><au>C. J.
Smith.</au></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Im"pi*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Im"pi*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impire</ent>⟦br⟧
